note.value:
Things get a little funky here, but it was inspired
by Asp.Net MVC. This controller does a little work with
reflection, so that new actions can be added without adding
tons of plumbing.

You'll see all decendants have an Index() method, which
is what will be called by default.

T extends AppState
This framework is naturally stateful, so a type was needed to store it.\nAppState is abstract and intended to be implemented again with app specific state info
UserOptions represent the left side of a Matching Set. \nsuper.Options represent the right side

At first, this was part of IOutput.
However, there are some locations where I may want the user
to be able to render views, but not have direct access to the Output.

I wrestled with this for a while, and I decided to keep it separate.
Could be easily implemented with a SQL database.

the Equals override is meant to be used when Grading.
A GradableQuestion stores a "CorrectAnswer" of type Response, 
and then the user's response can be compared to it.

You'll notice there are only three types of Response.
First time this was drawn, I noticed that many responses were basically the same.
Represents a stateful user output.\nCould easily be a GUI based system.
Provides simple Navigation capabilities for Controllers.
